 for bestpractices and # Booking Detail

## Overview
Develop a comprehensive Booking Detail module within the LuxeFlow CRM that presents a full, lifecycle-aware booking record. This page must render the entire booking story from quote to post-stay, including timeline stages, itinerary, resort & room category, rate details, commission structure, payment schedule, deadlines, supplier references, attachments, internal notes, and approval flows. The Booking Detail page must integrate smoothly with the Operations Command Center and with the Booking Lifecycle & Booking Management systems, providing actionable insights and inline handoffs. All UI must adhere to the project’s design system, performance, accessibility, and security requirements. All data access and UI rendering must be robust to null/undefined values, with strict runtime safety as described in the mandatory coding standards.

## Page Description (Full Detail)
What this page is:
- The Booking Detail page is the authoritative, read/write record for a single booking. It consolidates every aspect of the booking: client linkage, timeline (quote → confirmed → pre-arrival → in-stay → post-stay), itinerary items (days, activities, transfers with times), resort and room category, pricing (rates, currency, tax, fees), commission structure and calculated net, payment schedule (invoices, milestones, due dates, payment status), deadlines and SLA items, supplier references, attachments (contracts, terms, itineraries), internal notes, and approval/workflow states. It also presents downstream actions (send proposal, issue invoice, request approval, create task, link message) and inline handoffs to operations teams as required.

Connected features and UI goals:
- Operations Command Center integration: surface booking in 7-day upcoming stays, payment due items, overdue tasks, approvals needed, and urgent alerts related to this booking.
- Booking Lifecycle & Booking Management integration: reflect lifecycle stages in the timeline, enable editing of stages, adjust payment schedules, attach supplier references, and enable internal handoffs.
- Shared data integrity: pull client, resort, and supplier data from the core data layer; ensure referential integrity and synchronized state across modules.

UI elements and visual guidance (matching the Design System):
- Booking header: compact summary including Booking Reference, Status (with stage badge), Client name (with avatar), Resort, Room Category, Check-in/Check-out dates, Total value, Outstanding balance, and a quick action bar.
- Booking Timeline: horizontally laid out or vertical stacked stages showing quotes, confirmations, deadlines, pre-arrival events, in-stay milestones, and post-stay wrap-up. Each stage displays timestamp, responsible actor, and a quick status indicator. Allow inline edits to stage dates where allowed by business rules.
- Itinerary Section: per-day blocks with day number, date, activities, transfers, and transfer times. Support adding/removing/editing items and reordering days.
- Rates & Commission Panel: breakdown by rate plan, line-item pricing, currency, taxes/fees, discounting, commission model (percentage/fixed/tiered), calculated commission, and supplier net. Show historical vs current changes with audit trail.
- Payment Schedule: list of invoices/milestones with due dates, amounts, currencies, status (paid/unpaid/overdue), links to payment gateways or portals, and ability to generate new invoices or update payment status.
- Deadlines & SLA: deadlines related to approvals, document deliveries, and task due dates pulled from Operations Center.
- Supplier Info: supplier contacts, reference numbers, contract attachments, and ability to attach new references.
- Attachments: document gallery with preview, versioning, and download links; per-attachment comments or notes.
- Internal Notes & Handover: private notes visible to authorized roles, handover templates, and ability to assign/Handoff to team members.
- Approvals & Workflows: display current approval requests, status, history, and actions to approve/deny or escalate.
- Actions Bar: contextual actions like Send Proposal, Issue Invoice, Request Approval, Create Task, Link Message, and Quick Convert to Booking / Quote from the detail view.
- Visual cues: consistent use of stage badges, dividers, cards, and left-aligned content; emphasis on clean hierarchy and scannability.

Visual guidance (as requested):
- The page should convey luxury, clarity, and efficiency with generous whitespace, soft elevation, and restrained ornamentation. Cards with subtle shadows, soft borders, and olive-green accents for CTAs. Typography should favor an elegant serif for headings and a readable sans-serif for body text. Interactive elements should feature smooth transitions, accessible focus states, and clear affordances.

Mandatory Coding Standards — Runtime Safety (non-negotiable)
- Supabase query results: Always guard with nullish coalescing for lists (e.g., const items = data ?? []).
- Array methods: Guard all array method calls. Use (items ?? []).map(...) or Array.isArray(items) ? items.map(...) : [].
- useState defaults: Initialize arrays/objects with proper types, e.g., useState<BookingsDetail_item[]>([]).
- API response shapes: Validate responses; const list = Array.isArray(response?.data) ? response.data : [].
- Optional chaining: Use obj?.prop?.nested wherever API data might be nested.
- Destructuring with defaults: const { items = [], count = 0 } = response ?? {}.

## Components to Build
- BookingDetailPage: Main page container with header, timeline, itinerary, rates, payments, supplier info, attachments, notes, approvals, and actions.
- BookingHeaderCard: Summary header with key metadata and action controls.
- TimelineComponent: Timeline of stages with timestamps, actors, and editable stage dates.
- ItineraryEditor: Per-day itinerary builder with activities and transfers, times, and drag-and-drop reordering.
- RatesPanel: Breakdown of rate plans, currency, taxes/fees, and commission calculations.
- CommissionCalculator: Logic to compute commission based on model (percentage, fixed, tiered) with supplier net calculations.
- PaymentScheduleTable: Invoices/milestones with due dates, statuses, and payment links.
- SupplierReferencesCard: List of supplier references with attachments and statuses.
- AttachmentsGallery: Upload/view/download attachments with versioning metadata.
- InternalNotesCard: Private notes with search, tagging, and handover templates.
- ApprovalsPanel: Current approvals, history, and actions to approve/deny/escalate.
- ActionsBar: Contextual action buttons (Send Proposal, Issue Invoice, Request Approval, Create Task, Link Message).
- OperationsCommandCenter Widgets: Reusable widgets to surface 7-day upcoming stays, payments due, overdue tasks, approvals, and alerts, wired to the BookingDetail context.

Technical details:
- Data layer abstractions: Use a BookingService with methods to fetchBookingDetail(id), updateBookingField(id, field, value), addAttachment, addNote, createTask, requestApproval, etc.
- State management: Use React hooks with useState and useEffect; adopt a global or module-level context for BookingDetail to enable cross-module data sharing where needed.
- Performance: Lazy-load heavy sections (e.g., large attachments, full itinerary history) and render as collapsible panels. Infinite or paginated lists where applicable.
- Accessibility: All interactive controls must be keyboard accessible; aria-labels on dynamic elements; proper color contrast.

## Implementation Requirements

### Frontend
- Use React (or the project’s chosen framework) with TypeScript for type safety.
- Components must be modular, reusable, and themeable per the design system.
- Data loading patterns: fetch with proper error handling; use data ?? [] safety guards.
- UI routing: BookingDetailPage accessible at /bookings/:id or similar route; protected by authentication/authorization.
- Form controls: Controlled components with validation and inline error messaging.
- Null safety: All mappings and array operations guarded with (array ?? []).map(...) or Array.isArray(array) ? array.map(...) : [].
- State defaults: Initialize all arrays with [] and objects with appropriate defaults; ensure no undefined usage in rendering.
- API integration: All data fetchers and mutators should align with the Backend/API endpoints defined below; include mock/fake endpoints for local development if necessary.

### Backend
- API endpoints to implement or integrate:
  - GET /api/bookings/:id -> BookingDetail payload
  - PUT /api/bookings/:id -> Partial updates (fieldset updates)
  - POST /api/bookings/:id/attachments -> Upload attachment
  - POST /api/bookings/:id/notes -> Add internal note
  - POST /api/bookings/:id/tasks -> Create task for handoff
  - POST /api/bookings/:id/approvals -> Create/submit approval request
  - GET /api/bookings/:id/payments -> Payment schedule data
  - POST /api/bookings/:id/payments -> Create invoice/milestone
  - GET /api/bookings/:id/suppliers -> Supplier references
  - GET /api/bookings/:id/itinerary -> Itinerary items
  - Any necessary endpoints to support the Operations Command Center widgets
- Database schema considerations:
  - bookings: id, reference, client_id, resort_id, room_category_id, status, dates, currency, total_amount, outstanding_balance, etc.
  - timelines: booking_id, stage (quote/confirmed/pre-arrival/in-stay/post-stay), timestamp, actor_id
  - itineraries: booking_id, day_index, date, activities (array), transfers (array)
  - rates: booking_id, rate_plan_id, amount, currency, taxes, fees
  - commissions: booking_id, model (percentage/fixed/tiered), value, supplier_net
  - payments: id, booking_id, milestone, due_date, amount, status, paid_at
  - attachments: id, booking_id, filename, url, type, uploaded_at, uploaded_by
  - notes: id, booking_id, author_id, content, created_at
  - approvals: id, booking_id, requester_id, status, history
  - suppliers: id, booking_id, supplier_id, reference_numbers, contact, contract_attachments

### Integration
- Data flows:
  - BookingDetailPage reads from a BookingDetail endpoint; related data (client, resort, suppliers) are nested or referenced and must be resolved with null safety checks.
  - Operations Command Center widgets subscribe to booking events or fetch booking-specific dashboards based on booking_id.
  - Booking Lifecycle actions trigger backend mutations (update fields, generate invoices, attach documents, create tasks) with optimistic UI updates and proper error handling.
- State synchronization:
  - Ensure that edits in BookingDetail propagate to connected components (Timeline, Payments, Attachments, Notes) via a shared BookingDetail context or state store.
- Error handling:
  - Graceful UI with meaningful messages if sections fail to load; all lists default to [] to avoid runtime errors.

## User Experience Flow
1) User navigates to a Booking Detail page via Bookings List or direct link from Operations Center or Client/Booking references.
2) Booking header loads with core metadata; timeline shows current stage and last update.
3) User reviews itinerary; can add/edit days and activities; any changes update the timeline automatically if business rules permit.
4) User examines Rates & Commission to validate pricing and profits; user edits if permitted by role.
5) User reviews Payment Schedule; can create new milestones or invoices; payment statuses update in real-time.
6) User views Supplier References, attachments, and internal notes; can add new attachments or notes, and reassign handoffs.
7) User checks Approvals section; requests or processes approvals; actions trigger notifications to stakeholders.
8) User uses Actions Bar to perform tasks: Send Proposal, Issue Invoice, Request Approval, Create Task, Link Message; operations may appear as urgent alerts on the Operations Command Center.
9) All changes are saved, with audit trails; the page indicates any conflicts or deadlines and surfaces upcoming due items in the Operations Center.

## Technical Specifications

- Data Models: See above for detailed schema. Ensure proper type safety in TypeScript interfaces:
  - BookingDetail, TimelineStage, ItineraryDay, ItineraryItem, RatePlan, CommissionModel, PaymentMilestone, Attachment, Note, Approval, SupplierReference
- API Endpoints: As listed; ensure RESTful naming, consistent payloads, and proper status codes.
- Security:
  - Roles: Admin, Agent, Ops, Finance
  - Permissions: Read/write controls per role for specific sections (e.g., only Admin/Agent can edit bookings; Ops can view timelines and approvals; Finance can edit payments)
  - Auth: JWT/session-based; verify access to bookings by organization and user role
- Validation:
  - All incoming data validated server-side; client-side form validations with clear error messages
  - Dates and times normalized to a standard timezone; due dates and SLA checks enforced
  - Attachments: file type and size checks on client and server

## Acceptance Criteria
- [ ] Booking Detail page renders all sections (header, timeline, itinerary, rates, payments, supplier references, attachments, internal notes, approvals) with correct data binding and no runtime errors.
- [ ] All array operations are guarded with runtime-safety patterns (data ?? [], Array.isArray checks) and useState([]) initializations for all array state.
- [ ] Edits in Booking Detail (timeline dates, itinerary items, payment milestones, notes) persist correctly to backend and reflect in connected modules (Operations Center, Booking Lifecycle).
- [ ] Operations Command Center widgets reflect this booking’s upcoming 7-day stays, due payments, overdue tasks, and approvals in real time or near real time.
- [ ] All API endpoints are covered by unit tests and integration tests (mocked data with null-safe handling).
- [ ] Accessibility checks pass (keyboard navigation, screen reader labels, color contrast).
- [ ] UI adheres to the LuxeFlow design system with verified visual style: typography, colors, spacing, and component behavior.

## UI/UX Guidelines
Apply the project's design system:
- Consistent with the LuxeFlow visual language: crisp white surfaces, olive-green accents, warm neutrals, deep charcoal text, soft gold accents.
- Cards with subtle shadows and rounded corners; dividers and clear section separation.
- Top navigation and sticky header behavior as described; responsive behavior for mobile/tablet.
- Data visualization is minimal; no heavy charts; emphasis on clarity and legibility.
- Interactive elements: accessible focus states, smooth transitions, and restrained micro-interactions.

